On january 3, 2012
pickupsticks
Don't just go charging into battle

My guys don't charge, they just kinda amble along.

My main objectives are to have fun (e.g. entertaining battles) and to test out new ideas. Fighting against armies that are almost certainly going to kill me off is often a pretty good choice for both of these aims. If I'm trying to figure out the best general setup for the troops then facing off against superior troops will highlight their weaknesses much better... and any kills I score are more satisfying.
Hopefully the fights are entertaining enough for other people too - plus I know doomys is collecting fights for vid clips and thought he might appreciate the chance to see the chopper in action.

So, yeah, thanks for the advice but I think I'll continue to ignore it... the 3 [T] a day that I could gain by careful enemy selection isn't worth the fun I'd be missing out on. Besides, it's good practice for finding new ways to lose in the next tournament!

(I also enjoy the exterminate missions for the against the odds drama... winning is great, but not the ultimate)

At about 1:00 AM in the morning, I stopped by at a local pub known as a truce zone for mercenaries for hire, bounty hunters between jobs, and outlaws in need of rest. I saw a mercenary, a bounty hunter and a man running from his own country at a table, talking about wars long past. The outlaw was quite sociable, and when he spotted me he invited me to the table. He introduced himself as Sir Raleigh, and his companions as Lt. Adrian Ford and Col. David Dixon. We talked a while, and then I decided to ask if they wished to join a unit I was creating. They all agreed.

Suddenly, we were attacked by giant rats. (http://legion-1396-beta.minitroopers.com /b/view/miss2). Col. Dixon was overwhelmed and knocked unconscious after charging in ahead of us, but we managed to fight them off.

Later that day, at about 1:30 PM, as we trekked through the woods we were ambushed by a scout detachment of an army known as the Order of the Sainted Trousers (http://legion-1396-beta.minitroopers.com /b/view/bat3). Sir Raleigh and I were wounded, but Lt. Ford and Col. Dixon fought off the two-man team and got us medical attention.

End of entry
